    </div>
    <div data-panel-type="warning">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path
            d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3"
          ></path>
          <path d="M12 9v4"></path>
          <path d="M12 17h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <span>Story Advancement will be handled in the </span><a
            href="/day-to-day-operations">Day To Day Operations</a
          ><span> section.</span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      <span
        >With those pointers in hand, let us turn to the mechanics of play.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>The Roll</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span>Most of your time in </span><a href="/table-of-contents"
        >A Severed Story</a
      ><span>
        is spent simply living the life of an innie. Now and then, though, your
        employee attempts something whose outcome is genuinely uncertain — and
        where the stakes matter. When that moment comes, your GM calls for a
      </span><strong><span>Roll</span></strong><span
        >. The Roll is the core of play in
      </span><a href="/table-of-contents">A Severed Story</a><span
        >, and we have kept it simple. Every Roll follows the same four steps:</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The GM identifies the </span><strong
            ><span>Core Principle</span></strong
          ><span> that the action most embodies.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The employee rolls a </span><strong><span>d20</span></strong
          ><span>, applying </span><strong><span>Confidence</span></strong><span
          >
            or
          </span><strong><span>Hesitance </span></strong><span
            >where applicable.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The employee adds all applicable </span><strong
            ><span>Modifiers </span></strong
          ><span>from the row of their LIEP (see </span><a
            href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a
          ><span
            >) corresponding to that Principle&#x27;s <strong
              >Parent Temper</strong
            >.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The total is compared against the action&#x27;s </span><strong
            ><span>Task Severity</span></strong
          ><span> to determine the </span><strong><span>Outcome</span></strong
          ><span>.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div data-panel-type="info">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u><span>The Roll Formula</span></u></strong></p>
        <p>
          <strong
            ><span>d20 + Temper Points + Kier Points = Total</span></strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          <span>Confidence and Hesitance modify the </span><em
            ><span>d20 result only</span></em
          ><span>
            — Modifiers are added after the die is read. See
          </span><strong><span>Confidence Vs. Hesitance</span></strong><span>
            in the
          </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a><span>
            for the full Confidence and Hesitance rules.</span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h3><span>Identifying the Core Principle</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span>Each of the nine </span><strong><span>Core Principles</span></strong
      ><span> belongs to a </span><strong><span>Parent Temper</span></strong
      ><span
        >. The Parent Temper determines which row of the LIEP is consulted for
        Modifiers.</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>FROLIC</span></strong><span> — CHEER, NIMBLENESS</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>MALICE</span></strong><span> — WILES, VERVE</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>WOE</span></strong><span>
            — VISION, BENEVOLENCE, HUMILITY</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>DREAD</span></strong><span> — WIT, PROBITY</span></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3><span>Modifiers</span></h3>
    <p><span>From the appropriate row of the LIEP, add:</span></p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Temper Points</span></strong><span> — always.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Kier Points</span></strong><span>
            — when the action serves the interests of Lumon Industries.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >Whether an action serves Lumon is the GM&#x27;s call. When in doubt:
        would the employee&#x27;s GM (in-fiction) thank them for what they just
        did? If so, Kier Points apply.</span>
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>Dear Reader,</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >I've added a third Modifier... <strong>Ricken Points</strong
              >.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em><strong><span> Ricken Points</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>
              are added — from the same row — when the action serves
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>your</span></u></em><em
            ><span>
              interests, or the interests of those you care about, innie or
              otherwise.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >An action can sometimes serve both Lumon and yourself. In that
              rare case, add both. Most of the time you will have to choose.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >This painful struggle of interests is an everyday occurrence for
              innies.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— Concerned Citizen</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h3><span>Roll Example</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span
        >An employee wishes to surprise their Floor Manager with a gift of song,
        as they have been practicing the Kier Anthem on their lunch breaks. The
        GM rules this is a
      </span><strong><span>BENEVOLENCE</span></strong><span> action.</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>BENEVOLENCE</span></strong><span
            >&#x27;s parent Temper is
          </span><strong><span>WOE</span></strong><span
            >. The employee&#x27;s LIEP shows 3 Temper Points and 1 Kier Point
            in the WOE row.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span><strong>BENEVOLENCE</strong> is checked as a </span><strong
            ><span>Core Competency</span></strong
          ><span>, so the employee rolls with </span><strong
            ><span>Confidence</span></strong
          ><span>.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span
            >The action serves Lumon&#x27;s interests (a kind, morale-boosting
            gesture for a superior), so Kier Points apply.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><span>Roll: 2d20 → 7 and 14. Take the 14.</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>Total: 14 + 3 + 1 = 18.</span></strong></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Task Severity</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >The GM sets the difficulty of each Roll using the following severity
        ladder. The Roll total must
      </span><em><span>meet or exceed</span></em><span>
        the target to succeed.</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Routine (Target 10)</span></strong><span>
            — the daily expectations of any diligent employee.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Demanding (Target 15)</span></strong><span>
            — requires sustained focus, training, or genuine skill.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Arduous (Target 20)</span></strong><span>
            — tests the mettle of even Lumon&#x27;s finest.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Heroic (Target 25)</span></strong><span>
            — the rarefied air of legend. Worthy of Kier himself.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >The GM may set targets between these benchmarks when the moment calls
        for it.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Outcomes</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Every Roll resolves to one of four outcomes. Natural rolls of
      </span><strong><span>1</span></strong><span> and </span><strong
        ><span>20</span></strong
      ><span>
        on the d20 (before Modifiers, and before Confidence/Hesitance is
        collapsed to a single die) override the total.</span
      >
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u><span>Critical Success</span></u></strong><span>
          — A natural
        </span><strong><span>20</span></strong><span>
          on the d20. The action succeeds spectacularly.
        </span><strong
          ><span>The employee&#x27;s stress is reduced by 1.</span></strong
        ><span>
          The GM may award a small narrative boon in addition to the success.</span>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u><span>Success</span></u></strong><span>
          — Final total meets or exceeds the Task Severity. The action succeeds
          as the employee intended it.</span>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u><span>Failure</span></u></strong><span>
          — Final total falls below the Task Severity. The action fails, and the
          GM narrates a fitting consequence.</span>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u><span>Critical Failure</span></u></strong><span>
          — A natural
        </span><strong><span>1</span></strong><span>
          on the d20. The action fails badly.
        </span><strong
          ><span>The employee&#x27;s stress is increased by 1.</span></strong
        ><span> The GM narrates a more severe consequence.</span>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span
        >The GM may also raise or lower an employee&#x27;s stress on any Outcome
        at their discretion, and may use a Critical Failure as a natural moment
        to introduce a
      </span><strong><span>Problem</span></strong><span> or </span><strong
        ><span>Serious Problem</span></strong
      ><span> (see </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a><span
        >).</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>When to Roll</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Not every action calls for a Roll. The GM should call for one only when
        both of the following are true:</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The outcome is </span><strong><span>uncertain</span></strong
          ><span>.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The outcome </span><strong><span>matters</span></strong><span
            >.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >If the action is trivially within an employee&#x27;s capability, or if
        failure would not move the story forward in any meaningful way, the GM
        should simply narrate the result. Some moments are better served by
        character choice than by chance.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Stress</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span>Every employee tracks </span><strong><span>Stress</span></strong
      ><span>
        on their LIEP — ten checkboxes arranged in five named
      </span><strong><span>Stress Ranges</span></strong><span>
        of two boxes each.</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Outstanding</span></strong><span>
            — boxes 1 and 2.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Satisfactory</span></strong><span>
            — boxes 3 and 4.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Tolerable</span></strong><span> — boxes 5 and 6.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>Poor</span></strong><span> — boxes 7 and 8.</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Terrible</span></strong><span> — boxes 9 and 10.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span>An employee&#x27;s </span><strong
        ><span>current Stress Range</span></strong
      ><span> is the label beneath their </span><em
        ><span>highest-filled</span></em
      ><span>
        checkbox. An employee with zero boxes filled remains
      </span><strong><span>Outstanding</span></strong><span>. </span>
    </p>
    <p><span>Stress Range matters because:</span></p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>Certain </span><strong><span>Special Attributes</span></strong
          ><span>
            are gated by Stress Range — for example, the Closer&#x27;s
          </span><em><span>Inappropriate Outburst</span></em><span>
            requires
          </span><strong><span>Poor</span></strong><span> or </span><strong
            ><span>Terrible</span></strong
          ><span> (see </span><a href="/corporate-personas"
            >Corporate Personas</a
          ><span>).</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The GM may impose </span><strong><span>Hesitance</span></strong
          ><span> on Rolls made by an employee in </span><strong
            ><span>Poor</span></strong
          ><span> or </span><strong><span>Terrible</span></strong><span>
            range, reflecting the toll of mounting stress on clear thought and
            steady hands.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>The tenth filled box triggers </span><strong
            ><span>Burnout</span></strong
          ><span> (see below).</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span>For daily stress recovery, </span><strong
        ><span>Problems</span></strong
      ><span>, and </span><strong><span>Serious Problems</span></strong><span
        >, see the
      </span><strong><span>Assessment of Current Stress Levels</span></strong
      ><span> and </span><strong
        ><span>Stress Related Circumstances</span></strong
      ><span> sections of the </span><a href="/employee-profile"
        >Employee Profile</a
      ><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Burnout</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span>When an employee fills the </span><strong><span>tenth</span></strong
      ><span> stress checkbox, they have reached </span><strong
        ><span>Burnout</span></strong
      ><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Burnout is a serious matter — but Lumon, ever the caring employer, has
        procedures in place to help.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u><span>Immediate Consequences of Burnout</span></u></strong>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The employee receives a </span><strong
              ><span>Demerit</span></strong
            ><span> on their next Performance Evaluation.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The GM imposes a Lumon-appropriate </span><strong
              ><span>consequence</span></strong
            ><span> — a visit to </span><strong
              ><span>The Break Room</span></strong
            ><span
              >, an unwelcome meeting with management, or any other corrective
              measure the GM deems suitable.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The employee must attend a mandatory </span><strong
              ><span>Wellness Session</span></strong
            ><span>.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>The Wellness Session</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span>A </span><strong><span>Wellness Session</span></strong><span>
        restores an employee&#x27;s stress to
      </span><strong><span>Outstanding</span></strong><span>
        — all standard stress checkboxes are cleared.
      </span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>Stress derived from </span><strong><span>Problems</span></strong
      ><span> or </span><strong><span>Serious Problems</span></strong><span>
        is
      </span><em><span>not</span></em><span>
        cleared by a Wellness Session. Those circumstances must still be
        resolved through play before their stress can be recovered.</span>
    </p>
    <h3><span>Three Demerits</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span>An employee who accumulates </span><strong
        ><span>three Demerits</span></strong
      ><span>
        over the course of their career at Lumon Industries will be
      </span><strong><span>Terminated</span></strong><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Termination is a corrective measure of last resort, reserved for those
        who have proven themselves unable to flourish within the Lumon family.
        Rejoice — your service has been honored, and a new candidate awaits the
        chair.</span>
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>Read this carefully.</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >Termination, for an innie, is not an early retirement or a
              parting handshake. It is the
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>end of your existence</span></u></em><em
            ><span
              >. Your outie continues on, unbothered. There is no recovery.
              There is no appeal.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >Avoid Burnout. Help your team avoid it. And if a coworker takes
              their third Demerit — consider whether Lumon's rules are still
              worth following at all.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— Concerned Citizen</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span>That is the core of play in </span><a href="/table-of-contents"
        >A Severed Story</a
      ><span>. From here, turn to </span><a href="/day-to-day-operations"
        >Day to Day Operations</a
      ><span> for guidance on running the workday, or </span><a
        href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a
      ><span>
        to see how an employee grows over a career on the severed floor.</span>
    </p>
  </div>
</ChapterLayout>
